<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-798-954  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 798 954.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 23 1989 v23 n43 p56(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Shell kicks up heels to Rumba; Wall Data's micro-to-mainframesoftware package has some fancy steps.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wexler, Joanie M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Shell Canada Ltd tested three IBM 3270 emulation software packagesbased on Microsoft Windows as a beta test site when shopping for aconnectivity package.andP;  Wall Data's $595 Rumba package was the onlyone of the three that could run multiple sessions under Windows;other features of the package that made it the choice for the IBMPS/2-based shop were Rumba's dynamic font sizing, its user-definedmacro keypad and its ability to use a mouse to select host filesfrom a dialogue box.andP;  Rumba's graphical user interface simplifiesaccess to such mainframe applications as database managementsystems, decision support systems, electronic mail and financialprograms.andP;  The version of Rumba being tested by Shell runs withthe Netbios protocol, although Shell hopes Wall Data will soonsupport Novell's Internetwork Packet Exchange (IPX) and SequencePacket Exchange (SPX).andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Shell Canada Ltd. (data processing)Wall Data Inc. (products).andO;Product:   Rumba (Computer program) (testing)Microsoft Windows (Graphical user interface) (computer programs).andO;Topic:     Micro-Mainframe CommunicationTerminal EmulationSoftware SelectionCommunications software.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>